85
0:7:2,92 --> 0:7:6,68
produced a document entitled
"Modern Money Mechanics".


86
0:7:6,68 --> 0:7:10,34
This publication detailed the
institutionalized practice


87
0:7:10,34 --> 0:7:13,55
of money creation as utilized
by the Federal Reserve


88
0:7:13,55 --> 0:7:16,38
and the web of global
commercial banks it supports.


89
0:7:16,38 --> 0:7:19,46
On the opening page the
document states its objective:


90
0:7:19,46 --> 0:7:21,5
"The purpose of this
booklet is to describe


91
0:7:21,5 --> 0:7:23,7
the basic process
of money creation


92
0:7:23,7 --> 0:7:26,46
in a 'fractional reserve'
banking system."


93
0:7:26,46 --> 0:7:30,7
It then proceeds to describe
this fractional reserve process


94
0:7:30,7 --> 0:7:32,7
through various
banking terminology.


95
0:7:32,7 --> 0:7:36,65
A translation of which
goes something like this:


96
0:7:36,65 --> 0:7:39,55
The United States government
decides it needs some money.


97
0:7:39,55 --> 0:7:41,24
So it calls up the
Federal Reserve


98
0:7:41,24 --> 0:7:44,3
and requests, say,
10 billion dollars.


99
0:7:44,3 --> 0:7:46,1
The FED replies saying:


100
0:7:46,1 --> 0:7:49,32
"Sure, we'll buy ten billion
in government bonds from you".


101
0:7:49,32 --> 0:7:52,19
So the government takes
some pieces of paper


102
0:7:52,19 --> 0:7:54,45
paints some official
looking designs on them


103
0:7:54,45 --> 0:7:56,52
and calls them treasury bonds.


104
0:7:56,52 --> 0:8:0,45
Then it puts a value on these bonds
to the sum of 10 billion dollars


105
0:8:0,45 --> 0:8:2,9
and sends them over to the FED.


106
0:8:2,9 --> 0:8:4,8
In turn, the people of the FED


107
0:8:4,8 --> 0:8:7,73
draw up a bunch of impressive
pieces of papers themselves


108
0:8:7,73 --> 0:8:10,86
only this time, calling them
"Federal Reserve notes"


109
0:8:10,86 --> 0:8:14,95
also designating a value of ten
billion dollars to the set.


110
0:8:14,95 --> 0:8:18,8
The FED then takes these notes
and trades them for the bonds.


111
0:8:18,8 --> 0:8:20,58
Once this exchange is complete


112
0:8:20,58 --> 0:8:23,96
the government then takes the ten
billion in federal reserve notes


113
0:8:23,96 --> 0:8:26,44
and deposits it into
an bank account.


114
0:8:26,44 --> 0:8:28,14
And, upon this deposit


115
0:8:28,14 --> 0:8:31,4
the paper notes officially
become legal tender money


116
0:8:31,4 --> 0:8:34,18
adding ten billion to
the US money supply.


117
0:8:34,18 --> 0:8:38,82
And there it is, ten billion
in new money has been created.


118
0:8:38,82 --> 0:8:41,38
Of course, this example
is a generalization.


119
0:8:41,38 --> 0:8:45,53
For, in reality, this transaction
would occur electronically


120
0:8:45,53 --> 0:8:47,39
with no paper used at all.


121
0:8:47,39 --> 0:8:53,4
In fact, only 3% of the US money
supply exists in physical currency.


122
0:8:53,4 --> 0:8:58,6
The other 97 percent essentially
exists in computers alone.


123
0:8:58,6 --> 0:9:2,98
Now, government bonds are by
design instruments of debt.


124
0:9:2,98 --> 0:9:5,13
And when the FED
purchases these bonds


125
0:9:5,13 --> 0:9:7,97
with money essentially
created out of thin air


126
0:9:7,97 --> 0:9:9,7
the government is
actually promising


127
0:9:9,7 --> 0:9:13,2
to pay back that
money to the FED.


128
0:9:13,2 --> 0:9:17,59
In other words, the money
was created out of debt.


129
0:9:17,59 --> 0:9:19,5
This mind numbing paradox


130
0:9:19,5 --> 0:9:23,8
of how money or value can be
created out of debt or a liability


131
0:9:23,8 --> 0:9:27,85
will become more clear as
we further this exercise.


132
0:9:27,85 --> 0:9:29,5
So, the exchange has been made


133
0:9:29,5 --> 0:9:32,91
and now ten billion dollars sits
in a commercial bank account.


134
0:9:32,91 --> 0:9:34,8
Here is where it gets
really interesting.


135
0:9:34,8 --> 0:9:37,68
For, as based on the
fractional reserve practice


136
0:9:37,68 --> 0:9:39,74
that ten billion dollar deposit


137
0:9:39,74 --> 0:9:42,93
instantly becomes part
of the bank's reserves


138
0:9:42,93 --> 0:9:45,73
just as all deposits do.


139
0:9:45,73 --> 0:9:47,69
And, regarding
reserve requirements


140
0:9:47,69 --> 0:9:50,5
as stated in "Modern
Money Mechanics":


141
0:9:50,5 --> 0:9:53,43
"A bank must maintain
legally required reserves


142
0:9:53,43 --> 0:9:56,66
equal to a prescribed
percentage of its deposits".


143
0:9:56,66 --> 0:10:0,549
It then quantifies this by stating:
"Under current regulations


144
0:10:0,549 --> 0:10:0,55
.


145
0:10:0,55 --> 0:10:6,23
the reserve requirement against
most transaction accounts is 10%".


146
0:10:6,23 --> 0:10:8,92
This means that with a ten
billion dollar deposit


147
0:10:8,92 --> 0:10:13,199
10%, or one billion, is held
as the required reserve


148
0:10:13,199 --> 0:10:13,2
.


149
0:10:13,2 --> 0:10:17,2
while the other nine billion is
considered an excessive reserve


150
0:10:17,2 --> 0:10:21,979
and can be used as the
basis for new loans.


151
0:10:21,979 --> 0:10:21,98
.


152
0:10:21,98 --> 0:10:25,15
Now, it is logical to assume,
that this nine billion


153
0:10:25,15 --> 0:10:29,2
is literally coming out of the
existing ten billion dollar deposit.


154
0:10:29,2 --> 0:10:31,48
However, this is
actually not the case.


155
0:10:31,48 --> 0:10:33,93
What really happens, is
that the nine billion


156
0:10:33,93 --> 0:10:36,1
is simply created
out of thin air


157
0:10:36,1 --> 0:10:39,43
on top of the existing 10
billion dollar deposit.


158
0:10:39,43 --> 0:10:42,64
This is how the money
supply is expanded.


159
0:10:42,64 --> 0:10:44,5
As stated in "Modern
Money Mechanics":


160
0:10:44,5 --> 0:10:46,47
"Of course they" -the banks-


161
0:10:46,47 --> 0:10:50,11
"do not really pay out loans for the
money they receive as deposits.


162
0:10:50,11 --> 0:10:53,51
If they did this, no additional
money would be created.


163
0:10:53,51 --> 0:10:55,3
What they do when
they make loans


164
0:10:55,3 --> 0:10:58,525
is to accept promissory
notes" -loan contracts-


165
0:10:58,525 --> 0:11:0,92
"in exchange for
credits" -money-


166
0:11:0,92 --> 0:11:2,94
"to the borrowers'
transaction accounts."


167
0:11:2,94 --> 0:11:6,42
In other words, the nine billion
can be created out of nothing


168
0:11:6,42 --> 0:11:9,21
simply because there is a
demand for such a loan


169
0:11:9,21 --> 0:11:11,66
and that there is a 10
billion dollar deposit


170
0:11:11,66 --> 0:11:15,5
to satisfy the reserve
requirements.


171
0:11:15,5 --> 0:11:18,0
Now, let's assume that
somebody walks into this bank


172
0:11:18,0 --> 0:11:21,35
and borrows the newly available
nine billion dollars.


173
0:11:21,35 --> 0:11:23,7
They will then most
likely take that money


174
0:11:23,7 --> 0:11:28,0
and deposit it into
their own bank account.


175
0:11:28,0 --> 0:11:29,8
The process then repeats.


176
0:11:29,8 --> 0:11:32,71
For that deposit becomes
part of the bank's reserves.


177
0:11:32,71 --> 0:11:38,8
10% is isolated and in turn 90% of
the nine billion, or 8.1 billion


178
0:11:38,8 --> 0:11:41,75
is now available as newly
created money for more loans.


179
0:11:41,75 --> 0:11:45,67
And, of course, that 8.1 can
be loaned out and redeposited


180
0:11:45,67 --> 0:11:48,63
creating an additional
7.2 billion.


181
0:11:48,63 --> 0:11:54,5
To 6.5 billion...
to 5.9 billion... etc.


182
0:11:54,5 --> 0:11:57,16
This deposit money
creation loan cycle


183
0:11:57,16 --> 0:11:59,43
can technically go
on to infinity.


184
0:11:59,43 --> 0:12:3,74
The average mathematical result
is that about 90 billion dollars


185
0:12:3,74 --> 0:12:7,44
can be created on top of
the original 10 billion.


186
0:12:7,44 --> 0:12:9,5
In other words,
for every deposit


187
0:12:9,5 --> 0:12:11,67
that ever occurs in
the banking system


188
0:12:11,67 --> 0:12:16,17
about nine times that amount can
be created out of thin air.


189
0:12:16,17 --> 0:12:19,89
Money-Jitters.
Ask the obliging Bank of America


190
0:12:19,89 --> 0:12:22,58
for a jar of soothing
instant money.


191
0:12:22,58 --> 0:12:28,985
M-O-N-E-Y in the form of a
convenient personal loan.


192
0:12:28,985 --> 0:12:32,0
So, now that we understand
how money is created


193
0:12:32,0 --> 0:12:34,5
by this fractional
reserve banking system


194
0:12:34,5 --> 0:12:38,57
a logical yet illusive
question might come to mind:


195
0:12:38,57 --> 0:12:42,38
What is actually giving this
newly created money value?


196
0:12:42,38 --> 0:12:46,64
The answer: the money
that already exists.


197
0:12:46,64 --> 0:12:51,63
The new money essentially steals value
from the existing money supply.


198
0:12:51,63 --> 0:12:54,65
For the total pool of
money is being increased


199
0:12:54,65 --> 0:12:57,14
irrespective to demand
for goods and services.


200
0:12:57,14 --> 0:13:1,4
And, as supply and demand finds
equilibrium, prices rise


201
0:13:1,4 --> 0:13:5,37
diminishing the purchasing power
of each individual dollar.


202
0:13:5,37 --> 0:13:8,3
This is generally
referred to as inflation.


203
0:13:8,3 --> 0:13:13,2
And inflation is essentially
a hidden tax on the public.


204
0:13:13,2 --> 0:13:15,0
-What is the advice
that you generally get?


205
0:13:15,0 --> 0:13:16,95
And that is, inflate
the currency.


206
0:13:16,95 --> 0:13:18,55
They don't say:
debase the currency.


207
0:13:18,55 --> 0:13:20,15
They don't say:
devalue the currency.


208
0:13:20,15 --> 0:13:22,4
They don't say: cheat the
people who are safe.


209
0:13:22,4 --> 0:13:24,2
They say: lower the
interest rates.


210
0:13:24,2 --> 0:13:27,83
The real deception is when we
distort the value of money.


211
0:13:27,83 --> 0:13:31,8
When we create money out of
thin air, we have no savings.


212
0:13:31,8 --> 0:13:33,35
Yet there's so called "capital".


213
0:13:33,35 --> 0:13:35,81
So, my question
boils down to this:


214
0:13:35,81 --> 0:13:41,0
How in the world can we expect to
solve the problems of inflation


215
0:13:41,0 --> 0:13:45,46
that is the increase in the supply
of money, with more inflation?


216
0:13:45,46 --> 0:13:47,43
-Of course, it can't.


217
0:13:47,43 --> 0:13:50,32
The fractional reserve
system of monetary expansion


218
0:13:50,32 --> 0:13:52,41
is inherently inflationary.


219
0:13:52,41 --> 0:13:54,64
For the act of expanding
the money supply,


220
0:13:54,64 --> 0:13:58,19
without there being a proportional
expansion of goods and services


221
0:13:58,19 --> 0:14:1,66
in the economy, will
always debase a currency.


222
0:14:1,66 --> 0:14:5,53
In fact, a quick glance at the
historical values of the US dollar


223
0:14:5,53 --> 0:14:9,0
versus the money supply,
reflects this point definitively


224
0:14:9,0 --> 0:14:13,52
for the inverse
relationship is obvious.


225
0:14:13,52 --> 0:14:22,43
One dollar in 1913 required
$21.60 in 2007 to match value.


226
0:14:22,43 --> 0:14:25,7
That is a 96% devaluation


227
0:14:25,7 --> 0:14:30,47
since the Federal Reserve
came into existence.


228
0:14:30,47 --> 0:14:34,56
Now, if this reality of inherent
and perpetual inflation


229
0:14:34,56 --> 0:14:38,57
seems absurd and
economically self defeating


230
0:14:38,57 --> 0:14:42,34
hold that thought, for
absurdity is an understatement


231
0:14:42,34 --> 0:14:46,78
in regard to how our financial
system really operates.


232
0:14:46,78 --> 0:14:51,45
For in our financial
system money is debt


233
0:14:51,45 --> 0:14:53,96
and debt is money.


234
0:14:53,96 --> 0:14:59,64
Here is a chart of the US money
supply from 1950 to 2006.


235
0:14:59,64 --> 0:15:3,15
Here is a chart of the US national
debt for the same period.


236
0:15:3,15 --> 0:15:7,34
How interesting it is that the
trends are virtually the same.


237
0:15:7,34 --> 0:15:10,55
For the more money there is,
the more debt there is.


238
0:15:10,55 --> 0:15:13,86
The more debt there is,
the more money there is.


239
0:15:13,86 --> 0:15:17,28
To put it a different way, every
single dollar in your wallet


240
0:15:17,28 --> 0:15:21,13
is owed to somebody by somebody.
For remember:


241
0:15:21,13 --> 0:15:24,78
The only way the money can come
into existence is from loans.


242
0:15:24,78 --> 0:15:28,57
Therefore, if everyone in the country
were able to pay off all debts


243
0:15:28,57 --> 0:15:30,19
including the government


244
0:15:30,19 --> 0:15:34,97
there would not be one
dollar in circulation.


245
0:15:34,97 --> 0:15:37,7
"If there were no debts
in our money system


246
0:15:37,7 --> 0:15:39,99
there wouldn't be any money."


247
0:15:39,99 --> 0:15:43,72
-Marriner Eccles- Governor of the
Federal Reserve September 30th, 1941


248
0:15:43,72 --> 0:15:46,1
-In fact, the last time
in American history


249
0:15:46,1 --> 0:15:50,42
the national debt was
completely paid off was in 1835


250
0:15:50,42 --> 0:15:54,1
after president Andrew Jackson
shut down the central bank


